# SSR Forge TS 🚀

A lightweight **starter boilerplate for SSR (Server-Side Rendering) backend applications** built with **Node.js, Express, TypeScript, and MongoDB (Mongoose)**.

It provides a ready-to-use backend architecture with authentication, roles, and basic modules for fast project bootstrapping.

---

## 📦 Features

- ⚡ Express + TypeScript setup
- 🧱 MVC-like structure (Models / Services / Routes)
- 🗄 MongoDB integration with Mongoose
- 🔐 JWT authentication (access & refresh tokens)
- 🍪 Cookie-based auth support
- 👥 Role-based access control (`user`, `admin`, `moderator`)
- 📦 Prebuilt User, Product, and Token models
- 🧩 Service-based architecture
- ❗ Centralized error handling
- 🌱 Environment variables support (`dotenv`)

---

## 📁 Project Structure


src/
├── model/ # Mongoose models
├── service/ # Business logic layer
├── routes/ # Express routes
├── middleware/ # Auth & custom middleware
├── app.ts # Express app setup
├── server.ts # Server entry point


---

## 🚀 Getting Started

### 1. Clone the repository

```bash
git clone <repo-url>
cd ssr-forgeTS
2. Install dependencies
npm install
3. Create environment variables

Create a .env file in the root:

PORT=3000
ATLAS_URL=your_mongodb_connection_string
JWT_ACCESS_SECRET=your_secret
JWT_REFRESH_SECRET=your_refresh_secret
CLIENT_URL=http://localhost:5173

4. Run in development mode
npm run dev

This runs the project using ts-node (no dist folder needed).

5. Build project
npm run build

This compiles TypeScript into JavaScript inside the dist/ folder.

6. Run production build
npm start

This runs compiled code:

node dist/server.js
⚙️ How it works
Development mode
Uses ts-node
Runs TypeScript directly
No build step required
Production mode
TypeScript is compiled via tsc
Output is stored in dist/
Node runs compiled JavaScript
🔐 Authentication

The project includes:

JWT Access Token
JWT Refresh Token
Cookie-based storage
Role-based access control
🧠 Notes
This project is designed as a boilerplate / starter template, not a full application.
You are expected to extend it (add sockets, payments, etc.) depending on your needs.
Keep architecture simple and expand only when required.
📌 Scripts
npm run dev     # Start development server
npm run build   # Compile TypeScript
npm start       # Run production build
💡 Philosophy

This boilerplate follows a minimal but scalable architecture:

Add complexity only when the project actually needs it.

No unnecessary abstractions, no over-engineering.

